TY  - JOUR
AU  - Barro, Robert J.
AU  - McCleary, Rachel M.
T1  - Which Countries Have State Religions?*
PY  - 2005
Y1  - 2005/11/01
DO  - 10.1162/003355305775097515
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 120
IS  - 4
SP  - 1331
EP  - 1370
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - Among 188 countries, 72 had no state religion in 2000,1970, and 1900; 58 had a state religion throughout; and 58 had 1 or 2 transitions. We use a Hotelling spatial competition model to analyze the likelihood that the religion market would be monopolized. Similar forces influence a government's decision to establish a state religion. Consistent with the model, the probability of state religion in 1970 and 2000 is increasing with the adherence rate to the main religion, has a nonlinear relation with population, and has little relation with per capita GDP. The probability of state religion decreases sharply under Communism, but lagged Communism has only a weak effect. With costly adjustment for institutions, the probability of state religion in 1970 or 2000 depends substantially on the status in 1900. This persistence is much stronger for countries with no major regime change than for countries with such a change.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/003355305775097515
ER  - 



